Package com.arondight.timezone

Class LocationUtil

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.arondight.timezone.LocationUtil
  • public class LocationUtil
extends java.lang.Object
    The LocationUtil deals directly with address location. Some TimeZoneUtil methods simply delegate directly to this utility. Location String Input A locations string is really an address or part of an address for anywhere in the world. The most important part of the address is the country or country abbreviation as 95% of all countries reside in 1 timezone. For other countries, like the US, Canada, Australia and others, more information like a state name or abbreviation or postal / zip code are required.

    This utility will do it's best to parse an address and find a TimeZone. If the utility cannot determine the TimeZone, the result of the function will be null. Multiple TimeZone Countries The following countries have multiple TimeZones where if only the country can be recognized versus some smaller more specific area such as a region, state or a postal code, the function will return null if defaultIfUnresolvedInMultiTzCountry is set to false, or the following if defaultIfUnresolvedInMultiTzCountry is set to true:

    Countries with Regions
    CountryDefault TimeZone ID
    United StatesAmerica/New_York
    CanadaCanada/Eastern
    AustraliaAustralia/NSW
    The following countries have multiple TimeZones, but are not currently supported, meaning they will always return a default TimeZone
    Countries not supported
    CountryDefault TimeZone ID
    BrazilAmerica/Sao_Paulo
    RussiaEurope/Moscow
    MexicoAmerica/Mexico_City
    AntarcticaGMT
    Example Address Locations Here are some example addresses and the TimeZone ID that they represent. The parsing algorithm looks essentially from right to left, so building number and street are not important. Country is required unless you are using the US specific methods. The alogrithim is pretty forgiving, but the address should be in a relatively standard format.

    US Zipcode Every 5 digit zipcode in the United States is in a specific TimeZone and this utility contains the data to determine the TimeZone from the zipcode. The majority of the time, the TimeZone can be determined by the first 3 digits of the zipcode!
